<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		Digital ritual becomes an act of smuggling in Frías’s practice, which rejects colonial divisions between the sacred and the technological, the virtual and the material. His portals do not represent spiritual experience; they enact it, creating permeability where Western frameworks impose borders. By positioning himself as "a smuggler of knowledge, practices, ontologies, and cosmologies," Frías shows how digital systems can become sites of animist resistance rather than extraction. His ancestors include Wixárika lineage, queer and trans kin, mycelial networks, and conjured protectors, forming an expanded web that refuses anthropocentric frameworks.
	</p>
	<p>
		This strategic refusal extends to his lunar archive, where placing queer Indigenous futurity on the moon becomes a form of temporal sabotage. The gesture resists settler-colonial notions of legacy and land claim, offering what he calls "interdimensional magic," a recognition that marginalized peoples have always functioned as sacred boundary crossers. His work channels rather than controls, allowing spells to move "through you and into the world in ways that often exceed your original intention." The digital becomes oracular not through prediction but through relationality, honoring consciousness in metals, minerals, and the "oil, wind, and sunlight that generate power." Frías shows that authentic digital spirituality requires recognizing technology itself as animate, ancestral, and already entangled with earth and spirit.
	</p>
</div>
